I want to help people. I want to work with kids who have been hurt. I want to help families who are having problems. I think I can be a good social worker. 

I want to help people because it is important to me. I have seen people who have problems but do not want to talk about them. I have seen people who use bad ways to deal with problems. I went to college to study psychology. I wanted to understand people better.

One day, I met a young boy who was afraid of his parents. He was being hurt. I talked to the police. I told them about the boy. I wanted to help. The police asked me to talk to the parents. I told them that I was worried about the boy. The parents did not want to listen. 

This made me want to be a social worker even more. I want to help kids like this boy. I want to help families.

I also think it is important to be fair to everyone. Everyone should be treated the same. I have always fought for what is right. I have spoken up against bad things. I believe in helping people. I want to make the world a better place.

This paper looks at two ways to see insomnia: the biological way and the sociocultural way. The biological way looks at genes and health. The sociocultural way looks at how things around us, like our race, place where we live, and money, can affect sleep. This paper looks at research about each way and talks about the good and bad parts of each study.

Sleep problems can be caused by many things. They can be a main problem, or they can be a part of another problem, like a mental health issue.  Main sleep problems are called Dyssomnias or Parasomnias. Dyssomnias are problems with falling asleep or staying asleep. Parasomnias are problems with strange things happening during sleep. 

This paper focuses on insomnia, which is a main sleep problem. It looks at how genes and our surroundings can cause insomnia.

The biological way of thinking says that some people might be born with genes that make it hard to sleep. For example, some parts of the brain control sleep. These parts have special parts called receptors. If these receptors don't work right, it can make it hard to sleep. One study looked at mice and found that a part of the brain that controls sleep has a special receptor called GABAB. When this receptor is active, it helps mice sleep. If it's not active, mice don't sleep well. This shows that genes can affect sleep.

The sociocultural way of thinking says that things around us can also affect sleep. For example, where we live, our job, and our family life can all affect how well we sleep.

This paper talks about three things about Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD). First, it says what CAPD is. Next, it talks about how doctors find out if someone has CAPD. Finally, it tells how a teacher can help a student with CAPD in a regular classroom.

CAPD means the brain has trouble using sound. People with CAPD can hear sounds, but their brain has hard time understanding them. They may have trouble understanding speech, especially when there is a lot of noise. 

We learned about CAPD in the 1950s. Doctors started to notice that some children had trouble understanding speech even though they could hear. Now, there are many tests to see if someone has CAPD.

CAPD can cause many problems. A person with CAPD may have trouble:

* Finding sounds in space.
* Telling the difference between sounds.
* Hearing patterns in sounds.
* Understanding changes in someone’s voice.
* Hearing one sound over another.
* Understanding what they hear.
* Knowing the order of sounds.

To find out if someone has CAPD, doctors use tests. These tests can show if someone has trouble understanding sounds. There is no one test that is perfect for finding CAPD. 

Teachers can help students with CAPD in many ways. They can:

* Sit the student closer to the front of the room.
* Repeat things clearly.
* Use visual aids.
* Give the student extra time to answer questions.

Twelfth Night show us that disguise can help people trick others. But it can be bad to keep up a fake identity. People may lose who they really are.

It is hard to stop being someone fake. Some people may not care if they are tricked. But some people will be angry.

This play is about men and women pretending to be each other. Why do they do this? Viola says she wants to be safe. 

“I’ll bring you to a captain in this town/ Where lie my maiden weeds, by whose gentle help/ I was preserved to serve this noble count…” (5.1.247-249)

She is in a new place and feels unsafe. Pretending to be a man helps.

But now Viola can’t be close to other women. She is also in love with Orsino. But she can’t be honest with him. 

“Boy, thou hast said to me a thousand times/ Thou never shouldst love woman like to me.” (5.1. 260-261)

This play shows us that lying can help people feel things they hide. Olivia falls in love with Viola when she is pretending to be a man. Maybe Olivia has secret feelings for women.

But Olivia also likes to look at people. She likes Sebastian when he comes. And she sees Viola as a friend, not a lover. 

“A sister, you are she.” (5.1.315)

German rule in Africa was hard. Some people say it was very bad, especially for the Ovaherero and Nama people. They were hurt much. But not all of German rule was bad. 

German rule was different in different places. Some places had good schools. In some places, schools were not good. 

In East Africa, the British found many Africans who could read and write. This is because the Germans had good schools there.

But in South West Africa (now Namibia), schools were not good. The German government did not help much. They helped white people more. 

This made a big difference. In other places, many Africans could read and write. But in South West Africa, most people could not.

There are many books about German schools in Africa. Some books are old, and some are new. Some books talk about all the German schools. Other books talk about one place.

There is one book that talks about South West Africa and East Africa. It says that South West Africa was different because there were many white people there.

South West Africa had good weather. Many white people lived there.

Popular music has many types. It is hard to list all of them.  Many types of music have smaller types.  Rock, rap, country, jazz, and folk are just some examples. Heavy metal is one type of rock music that has many smaller types. 

Heavy metal music is loud and strong. It often has dark songs. It started about 40 years ago and has changed a lot. 

There are so many kinds of heavy metal now that it is hard to say what it really is. It has ideas from other kinds of music. But it is important to know where it came from.

Heavy metal is a movement. It is about darkness. It is music with strong bass, loud sounds, and strong feelings. Metal bands are very good musicians. The music is also sometimes about drugs.  

In the 1970s, many people used drugs. This made some music sound crazy and different. Heavy metal music was new because it showed the darker side of feelings. 

Some heavy metal music is also influenced by the Romantic Era, a time when people wrote about dark feelings.

"Helter Skelter" by The Beatles is a good example. It is a loud and dark song. Some people think it is one of the first heavy metal songs. The Beatles wanted to show that they could make music as heavy as the Rolling Stones.

Henri Rousseau was a painter. He made art long before the Surrealist artists.  Rousseau’s art was like a dream. His painting “The Dream” shows this. 

Rousseau had big dreams. He wanted people to like his art.  But the art world was hard.  He had to choose: paint like other artists, or paint his own way.

Rousseau was born in France in 1844. He did not go to art school. He worked for the government. He was sad when his wife and children died. Painting helped him feel better.

Rousseau wanted to be famous. He saw other artists making good money. He wanted that too. But he made art the way he wanted. He did not copy others.

Rousseau’s art is different. He was not like other artists. He wanted to be in a special art group, the Artiste Français. But they liked artists who painted in a special way, not like Rousseau.

Many good people think that good things are linked to beauty. I think this is true. A writer named John Keats said, “Beauty is truth, truth beauty- That is all / Ye know on earth, and all ye need to know.”

We learn much in life from school and our experiences. But we seem to know good and beauty without being taught. Good things and beauty try to show us something, not tell us what to do.  When we study good things and beauty, we try to explain why something is good or beautiful. We do not try to make rules for making good things or being good.

We can never fully say what is good or beautiful. Talking about a painting, like the Mona Lisa, we can talk about color and shape. But these do not say why it is good art. When we like something, we often say, “There's just something about it.”

Art and good things can never be fully shown by words. A writer named Flannery O'Connor said, “A story is a way to say something that can't be said any other way . . . you tell a story because a statement would be inadequate.”

No matter how much we talk about a work of art, there is something more. I think this is what makes art and good things so powerful.

Good things and art touch us in a deep way. This link is strong with stories. Stories are about life and values. We care about stories because of what they teach us about life.

Germany is a strong country. It has a mix of culture. It is from the Alps to the Baltic Sea.  It is from Cologne to Dresden. Germany has a long history.

The name Germany comes from a group of people called the Germans. People have many ideas about where the name came from. Tacitus said it came from a group called the Tungrians. He said they were called Germans before they fought the Gauls. Julius Caesar used the word “Germanus” in his book. He used it to talk about people who lived across the Rhine River. He wanted to show the difference between the Gauls and the Germans.  Some people say the name came from a spear the Germans used.

Tacitus said the Germans were the first people to live in Germany.  He said they did not mix with other people. He said they came from far away. He said they came by boat.

The Romans lived in Italy. They fought the Germans. They wanted things from Germany.  The Romans did not live in Germany.

I look down. I see the thing in front of me. I look at it, but I do not feel anything. My mind works fast. It sees the thing, but it does not think much about it. My thoughts come and go. They are like water moving. 
Once, I read a book about drawing. The book said to look at a thing like a box. It said this helps to see the thing better. I try this now. I look at the thing in front of me. It is a brown thing. I want to draw it. I want to make a picture like the pictures of famous artists. They made good art. They used many colors. I want to make art too. 

I take a thing to draw with. It is like a stick. I move my hand. I want to make a picture. I think of water. It is smooth and clear. The brown thing is not smooth. It is hard. I push it with my hand. It does not move. I push it again. It still does not move.

I am tired. I wear a tie. It is green. I do not like it. I look at the brown thing again. It is bad. Someone put it there. They are mean.

I get a thing to clean with. I try to clean the brown thing. It is hard. I use paper. I wrap it around my hand. I clean the brown thing. I am done.

Young people die in car crashes. Many things make this a big problem. The National Institutes of Health say one reason is that young brains are not ready for driving. Young people also have little experience. This makes crashes more likely. They also speed, drive off the road, and have more rollovers. 

Young people drive with friends. This is dangerous. A study in California shows this makes more crashes.

Some states have rules for new drivers. They can only drive at certain times. They can't have friends in the car. But these rules are not enough. The problem is that young drivers are not ready.

A doctor named Marvin Zuckerman thinks 18 is too young for a driver's license. He says young people like to take risks. This makes driving dangerous.

If we let young people drive, more will die. Soon, many new teen drivers will be on the road. We need to stop this.

We can make new laws. Schools can teach teens about driving. But no one under 18 can drive. New drivers can get a special permit. They must practice with a grown-up.

We need laws that work for everyone. This will keep teens safe.

I looked at old movies made by Edison. I saw fifteen trick movies from 1895 to 1901. These movies use tricks to make things look strange. I looked closely at these movies. I looked at how they made the tricks and how some movies were different. Many trick movies are made in a room. The camera does not move.  The movies use long shots and medium shots. The camera does not use close-ups.

Many trick movies are made in a room. The camera stays in one place. This is like a stage. The people in the movie move from side to side. They do not walk towards or away from the camera. 

The camera does not move, so the shots are long. The camera does not use close-ups.  The movies are short. Most are one minute or less. They show tricks like magic and disappearing acts.

Most trick movies are made in one shot. This means the movie is one long shot.

Some movies use many shots to make a trick. For example, in The Execution of Mary, Queen of Scots, the movie looks like one shot. But, there are many shots put together to make the trick.

John Taylor was a strong supporter of Republican ideas. 
He was mostly a farmer. But his work and time in government made him known for speaking up about freedom and how the government should work.  He liked farming a lot. This made him think about how the government should work. He wanted to protect farming. He used this idea when he talked about how the country should be run. He talked about how the government should be run, the laws, and even the courts.


John Taylor thought the United States had a good chance to make a great system because there were no old ideas to stop them.  He believed people have basic rights that are important. He said if one right is lost, they all become weaker. These rights should be safe from the government.  He said that in a time without rules, strong people might take advantage of others. But in a society, that should not be allowed.


To make a good society, Taylor said the government needs to understand that people can be both good and bad. He thought people were good and bad. He said, "Government is run by people, so it will have both good and bad."  He said good laws protect people's things, help farmers, and do not encourage too much business. He thought a good government would be fair no matter who was in charge. He knew people want things for themselves, but that was only bad if it hurt others. A good government keeps people in line, but it needs to be watched carefully so it does not become bad.


Taylor, like many other Republicans, wanted the government to follow the Constitution closely. He wanted a small government with only the powers the Constitution gave it. He knew a big government cost a lot of money and could become too powerful. But he also said that just following the words of the Constitution could be dangerous. He said you have to understand what the people who wrote it meant. He thought the Declaration of Independence was more important because it said the country was made up of states, not one big nation.

The project had a big drop in commuter logs in the third month. This was sad. We do not know why this happened. In winter, fewer people walk or bike. This may be part of the reason. December is the end of the school year. People are busy with schoolwork. Filling out the log may not be important. December is also a busy time for holidays. Students and teachers have a break. They do not need to come to school. Classes start again in late January, which may explain low logs for that month. But this does not explain the low logs in February.


Maybe people were excited at the start of the project. Then, excitement went down. We wanted to keep people interested. We created Carpool Challenge Week in March. This helped increase logs.  

One problem is that people like to drive. It is part of our culture. We gave out prizes to encourage people to use other ways to get to school. We gave gift cards to stores and restaurants. It would be interesting to see if big prizes, like a bike or a car, would help more.

We did not change the prizes during the project. If we had given bigger prizes later, maybe more people would have participated.

An ETF is like a basket of things you can buy on the stock market. It follows a group of items, like stocks or things like gold. An ETF is like a stock because you can buy and sell it just like a stock.  But it is also like a special kind of investment fund. ETFs are good because they let you put your money in many things at once. This helps reduce risk. ETFs also cost less than some other types of funds. But, you have to pay a fee every time you buy or sell an ETF. 

There are many different kinds of ETFs. Before you buy one, it is good to check if it does what it says it does.  

We will look at one ETF called IHF. We will compare it to the ten things in it that have the most value. We want to see if it is better to buy the ETF or to buy each of these ten things separately.

We will look at how much money each thing in the ETF makes and how risky it is.

“Dream-Land” is one of Edgar Allan Poe’s good poems. In “Dream-Land,” Poe uses the word “Thulé” many times. This word is from the writer Virgil. Virgil used it for an island north of England. The Greeks thought this was the end of the world. Virgil did use the word. Poe liked German writers. 

This is important. It shows Poe knew about Goethe’s writing. Karl J. Arndt says Poe copied Goethe’s poem. Oxford says Goethe wrote the famous poem “Faust.” It has two parts. The first was published in 1808. The second was published in 1832, the year Goethe died. 

In “Faust,” there is a short poem called “The King of Thulé.” It is about a king. His wife dies after she gives him a cup. The king drinks too much and cries. He is sad. He thinks it is his time to die. He gives his things to his children except the cup. He walks to a cliff, throws the cup in the sea, closes his eyes, and dies. The king in “Dream-Land” is like this king. 

Poe used “Thulé” twice in his writing. Once in “The Pit and the Pendulum.” But he uses it twice in “Dream-Land.” “The King of Thulé” and “Dream-Land” are like friends. 

In “Dream-Land,” the speaker talks about a dark place. He is lonely. He sees dead friends. The world is not colorful. This is like “The King of Thulé.” Goethe has lost his wife, is lonely, and does not want to live. Poe’s poem is like stepping into Goethe’s.


Poe knew Goethe. He liked Tennyson. He said so. Poe would also have read Goethe’s work because many copies were made after the first time it was published.

A person can get hurt in a store.  If the store is not safe, the person can ask for money. This money is called punitive damages.

In California, a person can ask for punitive damages if the store acted badly. The store must have known it was doing something wrong. The store must have not cared about hurting people. 

Jennifer Palmer fell in a store because of applesauce. She hurt her back. The store manager knew about the applesauce. He did not clean it up. 

Palmer can ask for punitive damages.  She can say the manager knew cleaning the applesauce was important. He did not care about people getting hurt. 

The manager knew people had fallen before.  He still did not clean up the applesauce. This shows he did not care.

The manager said he was eating dinner. This is not a good reason not to clean up the applesauce.

Four years ago, I took a class about Islam at CBC. We talked a lot about if Islam is a bad religion. This is still a big question today. Since 9/11, I see the news talk about Islam a lot. At first, it was bad. Now, it is very good. I do not think in 2001 we could have had a president named Barack Obama. He comes from a Muslim family.

The story of Muhammad is interesting. I thought Muhammad forced people to be Muslims. He fought and took over groups of people. They had to be Muslim. But the book says Muhammad was a good man. He was quiet and kind. People liked him. They came to him and wanted to learn.

There are things in the story that are like Jesus' story. Muhammad made food appear for many people. This makes Muhammad seem like a good man. But, it is like people are copying Jesus' story.

Some stories are not from people who saw things. They are from stories told to other people. This makes the stories seem less true.

The book says Muhammad was a good man. But history says he was not. I wonder if Muslims know the real story.

Jesus teach good things.  People did not always follow his teach.  

Christianity grew big.  It change over time.  Now, many people want to go back to Jesus's teach.

People like old ideas.  New ideas come slow.  But many Christians want to know what Jesus really said.

It will take time.  But people will find Jesus's true words.  They will take away ideas that came later.

Christianity will be more like it was when Jesus lived.  People will worship like Jesus's time.  

Many different groups in Christianity will become more like each other.

This is how history work.  Things change and then change back.  

Slavery in America was bad.  Now, Black people are leaders.

Christianity will change again.  People will go back to Jesus's teach.

People will read Jesus's words in a new way.  They will see them as ideas, not just facts.

Before Jesus, there was Judaism.  Jewish people had many ideas.  They had one God.  They read old books.

The Jungle show how people are self-centered. They want the best for them. They do not care about others. The book show this in many ways.

The owners of the factories are greedy. They want to make more money. They do not care about the people who work for them or the bad things that happen to them. Upton Sinclair write, "The line of the buildings stood clear-cut and black against the sky; here and there out of the mass rose the great chimneys, with the river of smoke streaming away to the end of the world". This shows the bad pollution from the factories.

The owners do not care about the workers. They make them work long hours. They do not pay them well. Sinclair write, "So from the top to bottom the place is simply a seething cauldron of jealousies and hatreds; there is no loyalty or decency anywhere about it, there is no place in it where a man counted for anything against a dollar".

The workers are treated badly. They have no help. They are like slaves. Sinclair write, "Here is a population, low-class and mostly foreign, hanging always on the verge of starvation and dependent for its opportunities of life upon the whim of men every bit as brutal and unscrupulous as the old-time slave drivers; under such circumstances, immorality is exactly as inevitable, and as prevalent, as it is under the system of chattel slavery."

Some writers use words in special ways to make readers feel a certain way. F. Scott Fitzgerald does this in his book *The Great Gatsby*. He joins words that do not usually go together to make a feeling. He also gives meaning to colors and uses them to make readers feel a certain way.

Fitzgerald uses colors like gold, green, white/gray, and red/pink. In his book, he gives white and gray special meanings. White means nice and high class. Gray means old and faded. Fitzgerald shows this at the start of the book. Daisy and Jordan wear white. Nick wears white to Gatsby’s party. People in the book are always wearing white. The only time people are not wearing white is at Gatsby’s party. At the party, there are many bright colors. Fitzgerald also uses white and gray to describe normal things. Nick goes down “white streets” to work. The names of people at Gatsby’s party are “gray names” on Nick’s list. Catherine’s apartment looks like a “white cake” – everything is the same. Fitzgerald also uses white and gray for simple people and places. Daisy and Jordan had a “white girlhood.” The valley of ashes has “gray cars” and “gray land.”

Fitzgerald uses white and gray to show what is not important. He uses this with Daisy. After a long time without using white and gray, Fitzgerald describes Daisy in a “white car.” Readers see Daisy as less important, like something Gatsby wants. Fitzgerald continues to use white and gray to show Daisy is not important. Her fur collar is a “gray haze.” She wears a “white dress” before Gatsby and Tom meet.

San Diego is good for farming. The weather is nice and sunny. Farmers grow many things there. Some crops are: tomatoes, oranges, lemons, lettuce, squash, broccoli, herbs, peaches, berries, honey, and peppers. Lots of people in San Diego like to buy food from farms that do not use chemicals. 

Many farms give tours. People can see how food is grown. They can also walk, watch birds, and do other things. This is good for the farm.  

Organic farming is good for the land. It helps plants and animals. But it can be hard work. It needs more people to help and more care. People need to remove bugs and weeds without chemicals.

The land we talk about is near a town called Potrero. It is 160 acres. It has plants and trees. It is next to a big forest.  Many kinds of plants and animals live there. Some are in danger of disappearing.

The land has been used for many years. People lived there a long time ago. Then they grew things like food and wood.

Culture is big in any talk. Culture is what a group is like. It is not easy to say what culture is. Culture is not the same for all people. It is not one thing. Saying all Japanese are nice or all Russians are strong is not true. It is better to think about how culture affects a talk.

When you talk to people from another place, you see their culture in a way that you understand. You will compare it to your own culture.

To understand another culture, learn about its history and beliefs. Do not judge or change it. Accept it and work with it. This is especially true when you are not strong in the talk.

If you are in a new place, show respect for their ways. This will help you talk better.

Culture is not just about countries. Companies have their own culture too. Some companies have long work days, others have short days. You can see culture in how people dress, how they talk, and how they work.

Some companies help people who are in need. Others only help with special groups. Look at how companies are different in America. This shows how many different ideas there are.

Values are even more important.  They tell you why a culture does things.  

If saving face is important, people will not shame others in a talk. If a hard bargain is important, people will not give up easily.

Learn about your partners before you talk. This will help you talk better.

People say that there is no God. This is in a book called the Bible. Two men, St. Anselm and St. Thomas Aquinas, said that God does exist. They both think about God in different ways. 

St. Anselm says we can know God is real by thinking about him. He says God is in our minds. We know God is real because we think about him. 

St. Thomas Aquinas says we can know God is real by looking at the world. He says there are five things in the world that show God is real. He calls these things “arguments.”

Some people think that St. Anselm is right. Some people think that St. Thomas is right.

Long ago, a prince was born. This prince became Buddha. Buddha saw the world and knew it had much pain. He left his life and found peace. This peace became the start of Buddhism.  

Buddhism is very old. It is over two thousand years old. Today, Buddhism is different. This is true in many places. For example, in Sri Lanka, there is a big water ceremony. Monks and people join. This is a special event. Buddha did not talk about this ceremony.

Buddhism has changed in many ways. It changed because of things inside and outside the religion. Some things helped Buddhism. Some things hurt Buddhism.

In this talk, we will use some words a lot. 

* Inside: Something from people who follow Buddhism.

* Outside: Something from people who do not follow Buddhism.

* Help: Something that makes Buddhism better.

* Hurt: Something that makes Buddhism worse. 

First, we will learn about the basic ideas of Buddhism. Buddhists find peace in three things: Buddha, the teaching of Buddha (Dhamma), and the group of monks (Sangha). The teaching of Buddha is written in books called the Tripitaka. They have three parts:
* Sutta: Stories about Buddha.
* Vinaya: Rules for monks.
* Abhidhamma: Ideas about how the world works.

Buddhism says that life is full of pain. We want things, and this makes us unhappy. We can stop this pain by understanding these things.  

The most important idea in Buddhism is the Four Noble Truths. 

1. Life is full of pain.

2. Our wanting things causes pain.

3. We can stop wanting things.

4. We can find peace by stopping wanting things.

The United States and Mexico were rivals for a long time. This went on for fifty-seven years, from 1836 to 1893.  They had many problems.  The biggest problem was the war, the Mexican-American War, in 1846 to 1848. The United States won the war. The United States took Texas and the American Southwest. 

Many small fights happened between the two nations. These fights stopped right before World War One.  The United States and Mexico had problems with religion, culture, and ways of life. They also wanted the same things. This is like many other nations that are near each other. Nations that share a border often have problems.

The United States had problems with Mexico and Cuba.  David M. Pletcher said that the United States had big problems with Mexico and Cuba. These nations are close to the United States. Other nations in Latin America had good relations with the United States.

Religion was a big problem. In the 1800s, Americans did not like Catholicism. They also did not like kings and queens. This is like the Cold War. America fought against communism and fascism.

The United States and Mexico did not trust each other. The English and Spanish did not trust each other. This made it hard for the United States and Mexico to be friends.

There were many fights between Mexico and the United States. Most of the fights were about land. Bandits would move from American towns into Mexico. This was a big problem until both nations used their armies to stop it.

The rivalry stopped when Mexico needed the United States. The United States wanted to help Mexico's economy.

Fifteen years ago, I got sick. I did not know why. I was a nurse. I chose this job for safety. People always need nurses.  

I wanted to be a scientist or a writer, but I chose nursing. Now, I am not able to work. I am 46 and alone. I have no money. I get money from the government, but it is not much. 

Life is hard. I do not know what will happen next. But, I know I am lucky. My family and friends help me. They are my strength.

Bad things happen to people. We need to help each other. We need to trust each other. 

Some people say Americans should be strong and do everything alone. But, our country was built by people who helped each other. They shared food and helped each other when things were hard.

So, be ready for bad times. Have food and water. Be prepared. 

But, also, be kind to your neighbors. Talk to them. Help them.

Why do living things change over time? Are there limits to how they change?  Even today, we do not have perfect ways to describe how living things grow and change using math.

Scientists have tried to use math to understand how shells grow in sea snails. This study looks at how math can help us understand how shells change over time.

We used pictures of sea snail shells to measure their shapes. We put these measurements into a computer program. We made new shell shapes using the program to see what kinds of shells are possible.

We are also doing experiments and studying real shells to learn more about how these changes happen.


A shell is like a tube that turns as it grows. Each turn is called a whorl. The whorls spiral around a center line called the columella.

The size of the whorls can change. The line between whorls is called a suture. The biggest whorl is called the body whorl. All the whorls except the body whorl make up the spire. The tip of the spire is the apex, and the other end is the base. The animal lives inside the shell and comes out through an opening called the aperture.

We can look at shells from different angles: the top (apical), the bottom (basal), the opening (apertural), and the opposite of the opening (abapertural).

To count the whorls, look at the shell from the top. Find the first suture line and draw a line down the middle. Count the whorls on each side of the line.

We can think of a shell as a series of openings that move through space and time as the animal grows it.  

We can use math to describe the path of the opening, and we can use math to change the path. This can help us understand how shells grow.

Indonesia has a problem. The rate of babies and young children dying is not going down fast enough. Indonesia wants to help people, but it is not doing enough to keep babies and mothers healthy.

Indonesia has made some good changes, like more people having doctors help when their baby is born. But some of these doctors are not real doctors. They are midwives. They cannot help if something is wrong.

Also, fewer children are seeing doctors when they have diarrhea. This is bad.

Indonesia needs to help more mothers after they have babies. Not many mothers get help after they give birth.

Indonesia does not do enough cesarean sections. This is a surgery to help babies born. Doctors do more cesareans in cities than in farms. This means people in farms do not get the same help.

Poor people in Indonesia find it hard to see doctors. This is because doctors cost money.

Indonesia needs to decide how to help more people.  

Should Indonesia make special programs to help babies and mothers? Or should Indonesia help all parts of the health system? 

Programs are good because they are easy to understand and work on. But they can be bad because they take money from other parts of the health system.  

Indonesia needs to think carefully about how to help all people.

Victorian books are know for being very detailed. They often talk about rich people from that time. Two books that are from that time but are different are *Oliver Twist* and *Wuthering Heights*. Both books have mystery and strange parts, which is not normal for books from that time. This makes the people in the books more interesting. We learn more about why they act the way they do and how they feel.

One example is from *Oliver Twist*: 
“And now, hosts of bewildering and confusing ideas came crowding on his mind. He seemed to be still walking between Sikes and Crackit, who were angrily disputing: for the very words they said, sounded in his ears; and when he caught his own attention, … he found that he was talking to them…. Suddenly he started back at the report of fire arms; and there rose into the air loud cries and shouts; lights gleamed before his eyes, and all was noise and tumult, as some unseen hand bore him hurriedly away. Through all these rapid visions, there ran an undefined, uneasy consciousness of pain, which weared and tormented him incessantly.” 
(Dickens, 220)

Both books use mystery, often in dreams.  But the dreams mean different things in each book. In *Oliver Twist*, the strange dreams show us about Oliver’s feelings and what is happening to him. When Oliver is shot, he dreams about it again. He feels the pain a lot. The dream shows how scared he is and how out of control he feels.

This dream makes us wonder who is to blame for Oliver’s problems. It is not his fault. He can’t even try to stop bad things from happening to him. He is very sad and feels like giving up.

I work in a program after school. I help young students. I like to help with reading and English. One time, I helped a boy named Adrian. He was in third or fourth grade. He had a hard time reading.  Some letters were easy for him, but others were very hard.  He spoke English well, but his reading was strange.  His mother spoke only Spanish. I did not speak much Spanish. We talked, and I learned something important. Adrian knew how to read, but he did not know the English letters well. 

I tell this story about Adrian to talk about a problem in schools. It is the language barrier. We must help children who do not speak English well. We must understand that it is not always easy to see the problem. A child who speaks English well can still have trouble reading.

What can we do to help? We need many things. We need to teach in two languages. We need to help children learn English. We need tutors. We need ESL classes.

The dual language system is good for all children. It helps children learn better. Some people are afraid of this system. They say it costs too much. But this is not true. If we teach in two languages, all children will learn more. We do not need all teachers to speak two languages. But we need helpers who can speak two languages.

When we are young, many of us hear about something big, something we cannot understand. Some go to church, some go to temple, some look inside themselves. Some believe what their parents teach them. Some do not. We may change our beliefs as we grow older. We all try to understand our place in the world. We search for meaning.

One day, I asked my father what his favorite bird was. We sat on the porch, listening to the rain. The rain made a loud noise on the roof.  He looked out at the rain. He looked far away. He was sick. He looked thin and his hair was not as thick as before. He did not look at me. I felt sad, scared, and did not know what to say. I hugged him and sat close to him. We watched the rain together.

My father died in December. He was sick for a long time. The medicine made him live longer, but he was still very sick. I did not know why this was happening. I did not pray. I did not think God was listening.

I did not want to see him die. I did not want to watch him go. I wanted to remember him as he was, not as he was dying. I knew him better than anyone else. I knew he did not want me to see him die. I stayed in bed for three days. No one called me.

The word "Gothic novel" is strange. It uses old ideas, but it is new.  The writer Ian Watt calls it an "oxymoron." He says it is like saying "old-new." People talk about Gothic stories in many ways. Some say they are bad. Others say they are good. Some say they are not deep. Others say they are very exciting. 

The first Gothic novel is called *The Castle of Otranto*. It was written by Horace Walpole. He used old ideas from stories about kings and knights. He also used new ideas from stories that people read today. He called his story a "Gothic story."

The Gothic story uses old ideas from times long ago.  It uses old buildings, old ways, and old ideas about what is good and bad. Many years ago, people used the word "Gothic" to describe things that were old and simple. They thought that new things were better.


 Gothic stories are popular today. People like to read about scary things and interesting people. They like to see how writers use old ideas in new ways. 


 One idea in Gothic stories is about knights. Knights were brave men who fought for what was right. They were loyal and strong. Gothic writers like to talk about knights because they want to show how good people used to be.  They think that people today are not as good.


 In the book *The Castle of Otranto*, there is a knight named Frederic. He is a brave and good man. He is like the knights of old. The stories about Frederic show how important it is to be a good person.

Supply chain is the steps to move goods. It starts with the customer and goes through making the goods and sending them to the customer.  A man named Keith Oliver made up the word "supply chain" in 1982. He said it is about planning and doing things well to make customers happy. There are six parts to a supply chain: making, getting things, keeping things, where things are, moving things, and using information.  Good managers use these parts to help customers.

Making is the first part. It is the start of the whole process. Making means knowing when, why, where, and how to make things. Managers need to know what customers want. They can look at the market to see what people want. Once managers know what people want, they decide what to make and how much. Then they decide where to make it. They want to make sure the best place makes good things and that people are happy. After making is decided, managers plan work and keep machines working well. Making is very important. Every small thing matters. If things are not planned well, it can cost the company money and time later.

The second part is getting things. This means deciding how to make things. A company might make parts in many different places. Each place has different machines, workers, and skills. The manager must decide which place is best for each part.  Managers can also give work to other companies. This is called outsourcing. Managers do this to make things faster and better while saving money.

Ellen Page is a star in the movie Juno. She is on a street. She has a sign. The sign says, “Hitler is alive in Burma.” Burma is a country. People in Burma do not have freedom. 

Burma is also called Myanmar. A group of people took over the government many years ago. In 2007, people in Burma went out to protest. The protests started because monks wanted change. Many people joined the protests. They are called “The Saffron Revolution” because the monks wear yellow robes. 

At first, the government let the protests happen. But then the government used force. The government hurt people. Journalists were arrested. One journalist was killed. Many people died.

This is not new. Governments have always tried to control their people. In the past, Roman leaders said they were chosen by gods. Japanese leaders said they were gods. Today, some leaders try to control people.

In 1989, people in China protested. They wanted freedom. The government hurt many people. In Rwanda, people were killed because of their religion. In Germany, Hitler killed many Jewish people.

Duke Ellington make good music. He play piano good. He lead his band for many years. Ellington make music for his band. He make music that is good for each player. He make music that sound good together. Ellington help his players play good. He make music that is new and different. 

A book about music say Ellington use voice like an instrument. A song called “Creole Love Call” show this. He use voice to make music sound good, not just sing words. 

“Creole Love Call” has many parts. The first part has voice and music talk back and forth. The voice start soft and then get strong. The second part is a trumpet solo. In a song called “Hot and Bothered,” Ellington make music with a trumpet and a singer. The trumpet and singer talk back and forth. The music sound good together. In a song called “It Don’t Mean a Thing,” Ellington use a trombone to play the song.

She want something. She feel this way for long time. It start when she about fourteen. She still feel this way when she seventeen. Now she know she want a person, not an object. But no boy want her. Her daughter know her mother in big pain.  "Okay, Mom. Where we go?" Her mother point. The daughter thank she took strong class. She carry her mother to the car, put her in the back, and drive.

In two thousand seven, the United States had a big financial problem. People lost jobs. Homes lost value. Many big companies had trouble. This hard time is still here. We must ask: how did this problem start? How can we stop it? 

The problem was made by bad choices by people in power. They made banks give bad loans. Banks gave these loans to people who could not pay them back. The banks made these loans because they thought they could sell them to other people.

Two groups, Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac, helped make the problem worse. They bought many of these bad loans and sold them as packages to other people. When people could not pay back the loans, the banks lost money. They lost lots of money.

The problem started long ago. In the year nineteen ninety nine, President Clinton wanted to be president again. He made it easier for banks to give loans. He wanted more people to own homes. This made the problem worse.

Many new kinds of loans were created. Some loans had high rates. Others were sold to many people. This made the problem bigger. People bought too many homes. They borrowed too much money.

When home prices went down, people could not pay their loans. The banks lost money. Many banks went out of business.

Ah, exposition. That part of your story where you show off your writing skills, making readers excited to see what happens next.  But exposition can also be boring, like a long lecture that makes readers want to close the book. Dr. Merlin, who is a teacher, knows this problem well. She gets frustrated when she reads long parts with no action. Exposition is like a little voice that tells you to explain everything upfront, instead of showing it through the story. 

Think of a movie.  Exposition happens when a character tells another character a lot of information at once, like a history lesson. In books, the author does the telling.

Let's say you're reading a story about a hero who met his wife, got married, and then her husband was murdered. You wouldn't want the author to take two pages to explain all of that. You'd want the author to show you the love between the husband and wife, how their lives changed after they met, and how much the wife loved him. This will make you care about what happens to him and understand more about the wife.

In short, you want more than just the basic facts of the story. You want to see the characters come alive and feel their emotions. You want to experience the story, not just be told about it.

So, as a writer, you need to show, not tell. Don't just say things happened; show them through your words.

I watched two news shows from Columbus, Ohio. The first show was NBC 4 this morning (August 13, 2011). The first story was about a man in Ashley, Ohio who hurt his wife. His name was Shad Hostettler. They showed his picture. The news said he hurt her many times and was in jail. They talked about the story for two minutes. 

The next story was about a man named Travis Buyers. He was 18 years old. He was hurt by a shot in the Sharon Woods area. He was very sick. The police did not know who hurt him. They have a team looking for the person. This story was short. I think this is because Travis was a black man. I have seen this before. When a white person is hurt, the news talks a lot about it. But when a black person is hurt, the news does not talk about it much. 

The next story was about a hole in a helicopter. A bullet hit the helicopter. A team is looking for the person who shot the bullet. They will give five thousand dollars to anyone who knows who did it. 

The next story was about the rain this weekend. They said it will be hot. They talked about the weather for a short time.

They also talked about a robbery at a store. A man robbed the store. He was black. He wore a black coat. They said he was tall and thin. I think they talked about his race a lot.

The next story was about a man named Rene Rodriguez. He was a drug dealer. He sold drugs from Texas to Ohio. He went to jail for a long time. They said he was Hispanic. I do not know why they said that.

Brothers have a strong bond. This bond can be good or bad. Brothers know each other well. They can see themselves in their brother. When things are hard, the true bond shows. This can be good or bad. Brothers must deal with the results of their feelings. A brother sees his true self in his brother's eyes.  A brother's actions show his true character.  In the story "The Scarlet Ibis," two brothers show this bond. They have many strong feelings. They go on a trip that does not work. They are sad and proud at the end. Only one brother lives. The story shows how the brothers feel. It shows the brother's thoughts and how he sees the world.

The brother has one strong feeling: pride. He wants to teach his little brother everything. He wants to race and climb with him. But the brother is sick. He is weak. He can't do these things. The brother is sad. He is mad at his brother. He even thinks about hurting him. But then his brother smiles. The brother feels love. He does not want to hurt him.

The brain is very good at working with information. People have used many words to try to show how it works. First, they said it was like a wax tablet. Then they said it was like a piece of paper. Then they said it was like a book. Now, they say it is like a computer. But we must remember that these words are just ways to help us think about it. They can not show us everything.

Our senses give us information. We see, hear, touch, smell, and taste. Our brain changes this information into signals. The brain then works on this information in many ways.

One way is like putting together a puzzle. We see small parts, like color and shape. Then we put them together to see the whole thing. This is called bottom-up processing.

Another way is like using what we already know. If we see a box, we know what a box looks like. This helps us see it faster. This is called top-down processing.

The brain also has a filter. It decides what is important and what we need to pay attention to. We see many things, but we do not see everything.

The brain also stores information. There are different ways to store information, like short-term memory and long-term memory. We need to keep information for a short time, and we need to keep it for a long time.

There are many ways to think about how the brain works. Some ways look at how people remember things. Some ways look at how computers work. Some ways look at the brain itself.

One way is to think of the brain like a network. Ideas are connected to each other. For example, “chair” is connected to “table” and “table” is connected to “wood”.

The people in the book live in a world with new technology and a system of money.  This system makes people want to buy things.  Huxley thinks this system is bad. He shows how it makes people forget about important things.

Many words in Marxism help us understand Huxley's book.  Marxism says that people in power control things.  This makes people think they are happy, but they are really being tricked.

In Brave New World, people are told they are happy because they have things. They are told to forget about other things.  This is like what Marxism says about capitalism.

The people in the book are like workers. They are told to work and buy things. They do not think about why they do this. The people who are in charge control everything.

The book shows that people in power can make people forget who they are. They make people think they are happy, but they are not.

Culture plays a significant role in any negotiation. Culture can be defined as much by what it is not as what it actually is and what it signifies. Culture is not homogenous, nor is it a specific thing. It is also not singular or uniform. Statements such as “all Russians are stubborn” or “all Japanese are accommodating,” are inherently broad and overly simplistic. While the understanding of a culture’s generalizations are appropriate, it is much more productive to a negotiator to understand the significance of a culture to the matter at hand, and how that culture’s attitude can and will affect the table talks. When one approaches a foreign culture, one experiences it in a way that is relatable to his own culture, and comparisons necessarily arise. 

Attempting to understand a foreign culture or mindset can involve anything from studying its history to realizing its prejudices. Rather than judging or attempting to change a culture, one must simply accept it for what it is, and work within its boundaries, especially within the scope of negotiation, and most especially if one comes to the table with a weaker bargaining position. Likewise, if a negotiator finds himself on “away” territory, a respect for traditions and beliefs can only help in getting over any cultural barriers and move the negotiation forward.

It is important to note that culture does not necessarily limit itself to a national/international dichotomy. Most companies within a given nation establish their own corporate culture. For instance, a corporate culture might emphasize long hours in the office or a more relaxed schedule. Evidence of a corporate culture can be seen in employee dress codes, in communication style (direct v. indirect communication, delegation of duties), and hiring practices. Some companies encourage philanthropy at any level from employees, others restrict it to “company approved” charities or fundraisers. One need only look at the differences in American corporate culture from company to company (and indeed, intra-company diversity exists even from region to region, urban to suburban environments included) to appreciate the diversity of thought that can reside within a particular societal culture. Certain cultures are not nearly as stratified as American culture, and may appear more uniform to an outsider, but a similar exterior is simply a sign to dig deeper. 

Values are even more important to understand, because they provide the why of a culture. If saving face or communal harmony are valued within a culture, it is certain that a negotiator will not publicly shame his company or his superior in order to succeed at the negotiation table. Likewise, a negotiator from a culture which gives greater weight to a hard-driven bargain will not necessarily be driven to settle at the earliest opportunity. Taking these generalities into consideration is important before one gets to the negotiating table. However, a negotiator is well-served to learn something about his opponent on a personal level in order to make the negotiation effective.

“The fool hath said in his heart, ‘There is no God.’” The preceding quotation is seen first in Psalm 14 of the Christian Bible, and is found at the beginning of St. Anselm’s argument regarding the existence of God. This belief seems to also be held by the other author whom we will be discussing, Thomas Aquinas. Because each of their arguments is in defense of the same concept, and our challenge is to determine who’s is the better of the two, we must, for sake of brevity, begin with the presumption that they are both correct in their belief in the existence of God, specifically the God of the Bible. To allow for a God-type figure that may not resemble the one in whom our two authors believe would not permit us to appropriately compare their two arguments, as they are essentially in defense of one specific concept of God. That being said, I would suggest that while each of them brings up valid points, neither truly provides a holistic basis for belief in God.
	To illustrate this point, we will first examine the basic argument of St. Anselm. Anselm’s passage reflects a path of gaining understanding through faith, looking within one’s self to find proof of God. He explains that because God exists within our understanding, we cannot effectively conceive his nonexistence. While this concept, when spelled out in his terminology, is a bit tedious and at times unclear, the basic gist of it is that the proof for God lies within one’s own mind. St. Anselm is suggesting to us that we needn’t go beyond the confines of our own soul to find truth about God, but that the existence of this being is found to be true simply by examining that which we inherently know to be true within our own minds. Foreign evidence is presumably unnecessary. This concept of accepting that for which there is not an irrefutable body of empirical evidence is often referred to within Christian texts as faith.
	This idea is very different from that held by St. Thomas Aquinas. Aquinas instead suggests that the existence of God can be proven entirely through reason and empirical evidence, with no need for faith of any kind. Such an idea would be beneficial in evangelism, an important element of Christianity, because it would enable the recruiting of new converts without any dependency upon their willingness to accept something that cannot be proven. They could instead be persuaded by logic alone. St. Thomas elaborates on five different logical arguments supporting the existence of God: change, causation, contingency, degrees of excellence, and harmony. In each he essentially demonstrates that the proof of God lies in the logical necessity for God. If you are told that that you are missing one puzzle piece, and assemble the rest of the puzzle, logic dictates that you can know of the features and the existence of the missing piece without having to see it.

Many authors use different ways to give their readers a certain feeling or attitude toward
important subjects. Some of these techniques are more effective than others. F. Scott Fitzgerald uses
many of these different techniques in his novel The Great Gatsby. Sometimes, Fitzgerald pairs an
adjective and a noun together that do not usually fit that way to give readers a certain aura around a
subject. Other times, he applies meaning to a symbol, and then uses it for this same purpose.
Fitzgerald uses this last technique with many colors, including gold, green, white/gray and red/pink. In
his novel The Great Gatsby F. Scott Fitzgerald builds up meaning for colors, namely white/gray and
red/pink then later uses that meaning to give readers a certain reminder of a feeling around an
important object.
The meaning Fitzgerald builds up and uses for white/gray is uniformity, with white being a bit
nicer and higher class and gray being more older and faded. Fitzgerald sets up this meaning in the
beginning of the novel with constant uses of both. Daisy and Jordan are constantly “in white” (8)—in
fact, everyone is always wearing white: Nick wears “white flannels” (41) to Gatsby’s party, Tom wears
a “white shirt” (36) when he meets Myrtle, and Catherine is “powdered milky white” (30). In fact, the
only time people are not wearing white is when Nick is getting his impressions of Gatsby’s party: “the
halls... are gaudy with primary colors” (40). Fitzgerald further defines these two colors in coloring
many common, unimportant subjects these colors: as Nick goes to work, he goes “down the white
chasms of lower New York” (56), the names of people at Gatsby’s parties are now “gray names” (61)
on Nick’s timetable, Catherine’s apartment is “one slice in a long white cake of apartment-houses”—
uniformity (28). He also describes plain or common people or places as white or gray: Jordan and
Daisy had a “white girlhood” (19) together, there are “gray cars” and “gray land” (23) in the valley of
ashes, the “Italian child” in the railroad is “gray” (26), and the dog-seller is “a gray old man” (27).
After Fitzgerald adds enough meaning to white/gray, he uses them to signify unimportance or
uniformity to certain subjects. This using colors to show readers something first starts with Daisy.
After a long time without any significant use of either of these colors, Fitzgerald comes out describing
Daisy as “dressed in white” in “a little white roadster”; readers begin to see Daisy as less of a character,
more like just a uniform addition, something that Gatsby wants and longs for (74). Fitzgerald uses
more of this technique around Daisy to give this impression of Daisy being a more uniform addition,
for example, there is a “gray haze of Daisy’s fur collar” (18), and she is again in a “white” (115) dress
before Tom and Gatsby’s encounter.

San Diego County is very agriculturally productive, thanks to a mild, sunny climate. Common crops include: tomatoes, citrus, leafy greens, squash, broccoli, herbs, tree fruits like peaches and lemons, berries, honey, and peppers. There is a substantial market for organic community supported agriculture food in the San Diego area, with many local organizations having lengthy waiting lists. Organic eggs and milk are also popular. Many organic farms also provide tours of their agricultural operations as well as access for hiking, birdwatching, and other recreational activities. This is the type of operation that would allow the landowner to gain the benefits of government programs while improving habitat, thus allowing recreational use and creating an opportunity for farm tours and other programs for making money or for educational purposes.  
	In addition to filling a potentially lucrative niche market, the benefits of organic farming often include greater biodiversity in plants and wildlife in the area thanks to a lack of chemicals in the soil and water. However, organic farming has greater costs than conventional farming in some ways. It requires more intensive labor and management to remove pests and weeds and fertilize the soil without chemicals, and losses are often greater than with conventional methods, while a small organic farm also lacks the efficiency of scale of large operations. Practices not related to organic farming but beneficial to wildlife may also incur greater labor costs, including planting cover crops, strategic grazing rotation, invasive species removal, and active management of plant growth to provide specific conditions such as edge habitat or patches of open ground. Thus, there are many reasons why the landowner in this example might seek financial help or expertise in maximizing both profits and habitat quality.  
The land chosen for this scenario is a parcel adjacent to the town of Potrero, in unincorporated San Diego County, California. It is 160 acres of chaparral, nonnative Mediterranean grassland, and oak woodland next to to the Cleveland National Forest. It lies in the East County Southern Foothills ecoregion of the San Diego Multiple Species Conservation Plan. The plan is still being reviewed, but presently considers over a hundred species of plants and animals. Many are endangered, such as the Stephens' kangaroo rat, the mountain yellow-legged frog, several species of butterfly, and the California gnatcatcher; others are declining and may soon be listed, such as burrowing owls.
	This area was inhabited by Native Americans for untold centuries and was then settled by cattle ranchers and cordwood sellers in the late 1800's. This piece of land was part of an original homestead patent and so was probably used for grazing and/or wood production for many of the intervening decades.
	 chose a piece of property from a real estate website and researched available government programs to see what options a small farmer might realistically have for mitigating costs and preserving wildlife-friendly operations.  As a model of what somebody farming this land might attempt to achieve, I located an organic farm in the same area.

There is a bond between brothers; an unbreakable, irrevocable bond. Within that bond lie many emotions: love, pride, jealousy, and cruelty, just to name a few. Brothers understand one another, far more than anyone else with that kind of bond, and they can only see themselves when looking at their brother. It is when a situation is at its most dire when the true nature of this bond shines through, be it good or evil. When these emotions become clear, they carry with them great a cost. Part of understanding the emotions born of this fraternal link is dealing with the consequences that they bring. When one can look a brother in the eye and see within that person their own reflection, they see themselves not as others see them, but as they truly are. In their actions and the consequences of those actions is where their true character lies.  In “The Scarlet Ibis”, two brothers explore this theme, and all of the raging emotions that accompany it. Throughout a lush, vividly described landscape, these two boys set out on a futile journey. Bitter disappointment clashes with intense pride in the climactic scene, and only one brother escapes with his life. The theme is expressed through direct characterization of the protagonist, Doodle, and their interactions with each other, as well as through the narrator’s point of view, which communicates the complex feelings experienced by the protagonist and his view of the world around him, both of which are heavy influences on his actions.
	The protagonist’s actions can all be summed up by one key emotion: pride. From the time he and his little brother, Doodle, first go out together, to their final, fateful excursion, the protagonist feels resentment towards Doodle. He had wanted a brother whom he could teach all of his worldly skills, like “…holding my breath, running, jumping, or climbing the vines in Old Woman Swamp…” He wanted a brother who could fill the role of “…someone to race to Horsehead Landing…and someone to perch with in the top fork of the great pine behind the barn…” Obviously these things are impossible, given Doodle’s condition. Doodle was born with an extremely weak heart, making in unlikely he would even survive. Even then, it was nearly impossible that he would ever participate in vigorous physical activity. What a blow to the young protagonist, his head filled with wild fantasies, to have all of those dreams crushed in an instant. In fact, he is even shown to bear some anger towards the small child, as he recalls beginning to contemplate killing him by suffocating him with a pillow. What kind of child would have the presence of mind to consider infanticide? However, his heart melts when the small child smiles at him. Such a simple act gave the protagonist such hope! This shows that his conviction probably was not very strong. In the back of his mind, he had an instinctive love for his brother.

The human brain is a complicated, creative information-processing system. As technology advanced from primitive to modern, the metaphors used to describe the brain also advanced. Initially, it was compared to a wax tablet, then to a sheet of papyrus, then to a book, and most recently, to a computer. As you learn about the brain, keep in mind that the usefulness of these metaphors is limited and can lead to erroneous conclusions.
Information processing starts with input from the sensory organs, which transform physical stimuli such as touch, heat, sound waves, or photons of light into electrochemical signals. The sensory information is repeatedly transformed by the algorithms of the brain in both bottom-up and top-down processing. For example, when looking at a picture of a black box on a white background, bottom-up processing puts together very simple information such as color, orientation, and where the borders of the object are – where the color changes significantly over a short space – to decide that you are seeing a box. Top-down processing uses the decisions made at some steps of the bottom-up process to speed up your recognition of the box. Top-down processing in this example might help you identify the object as a black box rather than a box-shaped hole in the white background.
Once information is processed to a degree, an attention filter decides how important the signal is and which cognitive processes it should be made available to. For example, although your brain processes every blade of grass when you look down at your shoes, a healthy attention filter prevents you from noticing them individually. In contrast, you might pick out your name, even when spoken in a noisy room. There are many stages of processing, and the results of processing are modulated by attention repeatedly.
In order for the brain to process information, it must first be stored. There are multiple types of memory, including sensory, working, and long-term. First, information is encoded. There are types of encoding specific to each type of sensory stimuli. For example, verbal input can be encoded structurally, referring to what the printed word looks like, phonemically, referring to what the word sounds like, or semantically, referring to what the word means. Once information is stored, it must be maintained. Some animal studies suggest that working memory, which stores information for roughly 20 seconds, is maintained by an electrical signal looping through a particular series of neurons for a short period of time. Information in long-term memory is hypothesized to be maintained in the structure of certain types of proteins.
There are numerous models of how the knowledge is organized in the brain, some based on the way human subjects retrieve memories, others based on computer science, and others based on neurophysiology. The semantic network model states that there are nodes representing concepts, and that the nodes are linked based on their relatedness. For example, in a semantic network, “chair” might be linked to “table,” which can be linked to “wooden,” and so forth.

In 2007, the United States of America fell into a crushing financial crisis. Unemployment increased, the housing market crashed, and many of America’s largest and most important corportations were left in ruin. This recession persists today, so we must ask the question: how did this crisis occur, and how can we stop it? In short, the financial crisis was created by selfish and naïve political decision-making that pressured banks and firms into issuing sub-prime loans into an already immature and unsufficient financial infrastructure. Meanwhile, Fannie Mae (FNMA) and Freddie Mac (FHLMC) were pressured to underwite and repackage these mortgages into CDO’s and CDS’. When borrowers defaulted on these loans, the banks were short on capital reserve and transferred this chaos onto the repacked mortgages that they had sold, and on to the rest of the economy.
	The financial crisis had its roots in 1999 of the Clinton era, as the President was aiming for a second term in office. He sought to extend his presidential tenure by augmenting his popularity. To accomplish this the Clinton administration relaxed lending restrictions, which helped to set the grim stage for the sub-prime crisis seven years later.  Steven Holmes of the New York Times reported in 1999, “Fannie Mae, the nation's biggest underwriter of home mortgages, has been under increasing pressure from the Clinton Administration to expand mortgage loans among low and moderate income people and felt pressure from stock holders to maintain its phenomenal growth in profits.” Holmes would go on to correctly foresee the consequences of these actions: “But the government-subsidized corporation may run into trouble in an economic downturn, prompting a government rescue similar to that of the savings and loan industry in the 1980s.” As detailed in the introduction, and as Holmes foresaw, ill-advised lending would certainly lead to the meltdown of the economy.
	Many factors combined to throw the economy into tailspin, one of which was the new and complex structure of mortgages. Adjustable-rate mortgages, mortgage-backed securities, and collateralized debt obligations (CDO’s) were all used extensively in the years leading up to the crisis, and only served to intertwine more sectors of the economy into the housing market. This led to U.S. households, and financial markets in general, to overleverage themselves in the housing market, leaving them extremely vulnerable to even small changes in price. 
	Indeed, the housing bubble burst, and the financial institutions that had bought these mortgage-backed securities were spited. The top five U.S. investment banks all together reported $4.1 trillion dollars of mortgage debts in 2007, which accounted for about 30% of the USA’s GDP. In the end, Bear Sterns and Merrill Lynch were sold exceptionally cheap, Lehman Brothers was dismantled, and Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley were forced to become commercial banks subjected to intense regulation. Fannie and Freddie were $5 trillion in mortgage debt, and were placed under government control in September 2008.

Ah, exposition.  That place in your story where you stretch your little writer's wings and take flight, astounding one and all with your magnetic, nay magical prose.  Or the part where your readers fall asleep and/or hit the "Back" button while cursing your name.  Dr. Merlin has been known to shout at her monitor when she finds herself in the middle of Too Much Information, and not even in the fun way.

Exposition is not your friend.

My gentle readers already know the basic writing tip, "Show, don't tell," but Dr. Merlin still stumbles into long passages of text where nothing happens, or worse, too much.  Exposition is the little devil sitting on your shoulder that says to get the history out of the way to get to the good parts (not to be confused with the devil sitting on the other shoulder urging the author to tell her audience every single detail of the childhoods of each character).

Exposition means telling the audience what happened, typically in simple prose.  In film, the exposition happens when one character tells another a core-dump of information ala "The Rime of the Ancient Mariner."  In fiction, the author's doing the telling.

An example is in order.  As you are reading a story, you are told that the heroine met her beloved at such a place and time, that they were married in a gala fashion, and that her husband was murdered in front of her eyes.  You would not expect this entire sequence to take two pages, during which time both he and she only get two lines of dialogue each.  You would expect the author to spend some time on the husband's character, evidencing by his speech and manner how deeply he loves his wife, and you would equally expect the heroine to show through big and small ways how much his presence in her life changed and enriched her (especially if the story were to tell you flat out later that this was the case).  A proper introduction to the husband's character would allow you to become emotionally involved with his fate and would give you insight into the heroine's character: what she saw in him, how deep their bond was, clues about her thoughts and beliefs and dreams as reflected through the prism of his eyes, and so on.  You would mourn his death with her, and so grow more connected to the heroine herself.

In short, you would expect meat on the simple bone of the storyline: "They met, they married, he died."

As a writer, you need to provide that meat.  (*looks at metaphor, sighs, plunges onward*)  Sometimes it is tempting to rush past certain things.  Perhaps you're introducing a new character and you know he used to be in the Air Force, and he's the night manager of a gas station now, and he was married twice, no kids, likes to go fishing on the weekends, secretly dreams of owning the gas station someday and had Eggs Benedict for breakfast.
